SIMPLE: forked
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Forked
<hw>Forked</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Formed into
a forklike shape; having a fork; dividing into two or more prongs or
branches; furcated; bifurcated; zigzag; <as>as, the <ex>forked</ex>
lighting</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A serpent seen, with <qex>forked</qex> tongue.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having a double meaning; ambiguous;
equivocal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cross forked</b></col> <fld>(Her.)</fld>, <cd>a cross,
the ends of whose arms are divided into two sharp points; -- called also
<altname>cross double fitch⟦eacute⟧</altname>. A <stype>cross forked of
three points</stype> is a cross, each of whose arms terminates in three
sharp points.</cd> -- <col><b>Forked counsel</b></col>, <cd>advice
pointing more than one way; ambiguous advice.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<au>B. Jonson.</au></cs></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Fork"ed*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Fork"ed*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forkerve</ent>⟦br⟧
